},"en":{"Abt 1150–1186":"about 1150–1186","1150–1186":"1150–1186","1161–Male":"1161–Deceased","1164–Male":"1164–Deceased","1160–Female":"1160–Deceased","1175–1247":"1175–1247","1178–Male":"1178–Deceased","1185–1247":"1185–1247","–Male":"Deceased","1120–Male":"1120–Deceased","1142–Female":"1142–Deceased","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","Abt 1175":"about 1175","Abt 1150":"about 1150","1247":"1247","1178":"1178","about 1178":"about 1178","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Europe":"Europe","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Hatton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of several places called Hatton (Cheshire, Derbyshire, Lincolnshire, Middlesex, Shropshire, Staffordshire, Warwickshire), Hatton Hall (Cheshire), or Cold and High Hatton (Shropshire). The placenames derive from Old English <i>hǣth</i> ‘heath, heather’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Compare   Heath  .","English: variant of <b>Atton</b> with prosthetic <i>H-</i>, a topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>). Compare   Towne  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Giolla Chatáin</b>, a patronymic from a personal name meaning ‘servant of (Saint) Catan’; see   McHatton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Hatten","meanings":["English: variant of   Hatton  . This surname is also common among African Americans.","North German: habitational name from the name of an area of marshland between Oldenburg and Bremen."]},{"name":"Hattan","meanings":["English and Scottish (Argyll): variant of   Hatton  ."]},{"name":"Aton","meanings":["variant of   Hatton  , with loss of initial <i>H-</i>.","topographic name from Middle English <i>atte toun</i> ‘(dweller) at the settlement’ (Old English <i>æt thǣm tūn(e)</i>).","English:"]},{"name":"Heath","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(on the) heath’ (Middle English <i>he(a)th</i>, Old English <i>hǣth</i>) or else a habitational name from any of numerous places called with this word. The same word also denoted heather, the characteristic plant of heathland areas. This surname has also been established in Dublin, Ireland, since the late 16th century."]}]},{"name":"Geoffrey","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Germanic (Frankish and Lombard) origin, introduced to Britain by the Normans. It was in regular use among the counts of Anjou, ancestors of the English royal house of Plantagenet, who were descended from Geoffrey Plantagenet, Count of Anjou (  1113–51 ). It was a particularly popular name in England and France in the later Middle Ages; notable bearers in England include the poet  Geoffrey Chaucer  (  <i>c.</i>1340–1400 ) and in Wales the chronicler  Geoffrey  of Monmouth (  d. 1155 ). The original form and meaning of the name is disputed. According to one theory, it is merely a variant of   Godfrey ;  others derive the first part from the Germanic word <i>gawia</i> ‘territory’, <i>walah</i> ‘stranger’, or <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’. Medieval forms can be found to support all these theories, and it is possible that several names have fallen together, or that the name was subjected to reanalysis by folk etymology at an early date."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Geoffrey de Hatton was born about 1150, in Cheshire, England, his father, Adam de Hatton, was 32 and his mother, Avice De Ville, was 9. He married Matilda Herthull in 1175, in Cheshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in 1186, in Hatton, Cheshire, England, at the age of 37."},"et":{"Abt 1150–1186":"umbes 1150–1186","1150–1186":"1150–1186","1161–Male":"1161–Surnud","1164–Male":"1164–Surnud","1160–Female":"1160–Surnud","1175–1247":"1175–1247","1178–Male":"1178–Surnud","1185–1247":"1185–1247","–Male":"Surnud","1120–Male":"1120–Surnud","1142–Female":"1142–Surnud","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","Abt 1175":"umbes 1175","Abt 1150":"umbes 1150","1247":"1247","1178":"1178","about 1178":"umbes 1178","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Europe":"Europe","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1150–1186":"noin 1150–1186","1150–1186":"1150–1186","1161–Male":"1161–Kuollut","1164–Male":"1164–Kuollut","1160–Female":"1160–Kuollut","1175–1247":"1175–1247","1178–Male":"1178–Kuollut","1185–1247":"1185–1247","–Male":"Kuollut","1120–Male":"1120–Kuollut","1142–Female":"1142–Kuollut","1175":"1175","1186":"1186","1142":"1142","1120":"1120","1164":"1164","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","1161":"1161","1160":"1160","Abt 1175":"noin 1175","Abt 1150":"noin 1150","1247":"1247","1178":"1178","about 1178":"noin 1178","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Europe":"Europe","Hatton, Cheshire, England":"Hatton, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"Abt 1150–1186":"environ 1150–1186","1150–1186":"1150–1186","1161–Male":"1161–Décédé","1164–Male":"1164–Décédé","1160–Female":"1160–Décédée","1175–1247":"1175–1247","1178–Ma